<font color="#FF0000">&quot;DON'T FOLLOW LEADERS....&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 24  5:49:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Since it seems to matter to some of you, I'm a 50 year-old high school social studies teacher who did not serve.  I did not avoid the draft, but certainly took full advantage of the deferment system while in college and, later, while teaching at the roughest junior high school west of East St. Louis.  Had I been drafted I do not believe I would have gone to Vietnam.  I never participated in any organized protests against the war, but wrote letters to various politicians and publications, and protested with my vote. I used to feel very guilty about not having served.  I thought then, and feel even more so today, that our country had NO business in Vietnam.  If communism is so bad, I ask myself, why did our country loan $30 billion to Poland in the '70's? Why are we trading with the Chinese today?  As someone posted on here somewhere, if we aren't supposed to hate people who have different religious beliefs, or people with a different skin color, or people........, then why oh why must we hate people with a different set of political beliefs?  Because our leaders tell us to? I'm sorry.  I don't get it.  Vietnam was a tragedy of the highest order.<br>
Our fighting men and women did NOT lose the war, our leaders did.  The protesters are NOT to be blamed for the way things turned out, our leaders are.  On amnesty- let 'em all come back.  As long as we keep sniping at each other, as long as we keep blaming each other, as long as we keep playing their game [see blacks vs. whites, U.S. citizens vs. immigrants, bloods vs. crips, pro-lifers vs. pro-choicers, etc., etc., ad infinitum]  our political/military/economic leaders will continue about their merry way exploiting us.  But the sad thing is, when we look at our leaders, who do we see?  A reflection of ourselves.  Talk about reality, how fucked up is that?!?!?  If you study the history of our nation, you realize that there will be more military &quot;involvements.&quot;  Always have been, always will be.  And you hope your sons and daughters ask the right questions before they &quot;follow leaders.&quot;  I believe Vietnam taught us all to ask questions (I could be wrong, but I don't think so). I'm just not sure we know all the answers or, and this scares the hell out of me, want to know all the answers.  <br>
                               Nurse Ratchet
